00:31:56.639 --> 00:31:59.230
All right.
We have a volunteer.

00:31:59.230 --> 00:32:14.240
Q So, I think one difficulty that we face
on this issue is basically communicating sort

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:21.369
of, What exactly the sort of global threat
that we're envisioning if we get to 450 parts

00:32:21.369 --> 00:32:26.309
per million to the general population?
Because it seems kind of abstract.

00:32:26.309 --> 00:32:33.559
Dr. Henry Pollack: Well, it does.
And the reason that ice may not be a perfect

00:32:33.559 --> 00:32:39.030
medium is that, the ice is a long way away
from where the people are, but the sea level

00:32:39.030 --> 00:32:45.710
change affects the entire globe.
And so, the task is to have people be aware

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:54.499
that, what seems to be a remote issue, in
fact, is one that has very direct consequences.

00:32:54.499 --> 00:32:59.919
Q And, just to follow up, so it sounds like,
based on what you're saying that, kind of,

00:32:59.919 --> 00:33:06.179
the direction that we're headed is maybe losing
lots of ice whether we get to 450 or not.

00:33:06.179 --> 00:33:10.510
Or maybe that's only if we get to 450, then
that's going to start happening.

00:33:10.510 --> 00:33:15.679
Dr. Henry Pollack: No, it's already happening.
We don't want it to go beyond that threshold.

00:33:15.679 --> 00:33:19.899
Some actually think 350 is the proper threshold.
We're already past that.

00:33:19.899 --> 00:33:24.940
They want to return as quickly as possible.
Bill McKibben is one who advocates that.

00:33:24.940 --> 00:33:34.639
But, I think that the answer -- the real question
you're asking -- is, we have to translate

00:33:34.639 --> 00:33:39.690
this into issues that are closer to home that
people do understand.

00:33:39.690 --> 00:33:45.961
And, in that context, I think that the global
financial crisis is a stroke of luck.

00:33:45.961 --> 00:33:51.391
Sorry that, you know, for all the people who
are out of work, that's no stroke of luck

00:33:51.391 --> 00:33:56.389
at all.
But it is kind of the lack in the head that

00:33:56.389 --> 00:34:03.269
I speak of where people say, "Gee, everything
we've been doing suddenly doesn't seem like

00:34:03.269 --> 00:34:07.769
we really knew what we were doing.
So, maybe we can take bold steps now.”

00:34:07.769 --> 00:34:15.399
And Al Gore said something like, you know,
"Our dependence on foreign oil and the security

00:34:15.399 --> 00:34:23.280
issues associated with that, our status as
the world's largest debtor nation, our financial

00:34:23.280 --> 00:34:28.720
instability around the world, and climate
change are not four separate problems.

00:34:28.720 --> 00:34:34.730
They're all four facets of the same problem
 -- a misguided, national energy policy.”

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:43.399
So I admire the way that Steve Chu and his
colleagues in Washington are focusing on energy.

00:34:43.399 --> 00:34:47.790
If we get our energy policy right, that's
something everyone understands locally.

00:34:47.790 --> 00:34:50.909
They don't have to think about polar ice to
get the message.

00:34:50.909 --> 00:34:58.170
So having that now as a vehicle to get people's
awareness and their creativity thinking -- going

00:34:58.170 --> 00:35:01.750
 -- I think is a good step.

00:35:01.750 --> 00:35:03.190
Q Hi.

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:06.069
Dr. Henry Pollack: Hi.

00:35:06.069 --> 00:35:09.450
Q Thank you so much for coming.

00:35:09.450 --> 00:35:10.450
Dr. Henry Pollack: Thank you.

00:35:10.450 --> 00:35:15.349
Q So, if you see that a lot of these things
are already happening, and you could see the

00:35:15.349 --> 00:35:22.549
change, my first question is, How do you still
sleep at night if you know that this was all

00:35:22.549 --> 00:35:23.549
coming?

00:35:23.549 --> 00:35:29.819
Dr. Henry Pollack: Well, it's a good question,
because I'm as concerned as any.

00:35:29.819 --> 00:35:37.050
And I don't lose sleep over it, but I do think
about it and try and think of, "What can I

00:35:37.050 --> 00:35:42.559
do differently to reach more people to develop
an awareness?”

00:35:42.559 --> 00:35:48.049
And so, while -- as I say, I'm not losing
sleep, but it has energized me during the

00:35:48.049 --> 00:35:55.700
day to explore as many avenues as possible.
And one of them, I should say, is that, people

00:35:55.700 --> 00:36:02.001
say, "Well, what can I do individually to
help mitigate climate change?”

00:36:02.001 --> 00:36:08.430
And, of course, you heard all of it.
You know, we want to have our houses more

00:36:08.430 --> 00:36:12.220
energy efficient.
We want to have our transportation more energy

00:36:12.220 --> 00:36:15.000
efficient.
We want to change lightbulbs.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:19.270
We want to drive less.
We want to choose where we live so we don't

00:36:19.270 --> 00:36:24.450
have to commute so much.
And all of those are important, personal decisions.

00:36:24.450 --> 00:36:32.049
I've even become aware of -- even rethinking
your eating habits is something that can have

00:36:32.049 --> 00:36:34.869
a big impact.
Because, of course, there's so many of us,

00:36:34.869 --> 00:36:40.890
and choices among foods have very real, energy
implications.

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:48.500
But, I still think that the problem is so
big that it won't come from volunteers or

00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:53.849
more individual choice.
We need both state and national policies and

00:36:53.849 --> 00:37:01.090
international policies that become from our
elected representatives, and so your vote

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:05.270
is very important.
If the people that go to Congress that represent

00:37:05.270 --> 00:37:08.859
you aren't representing you on this issue,
you should let them know that.

00:37:08.859 --> 00:37:14.339
And let them know, if there's an election
in 18 months, or whatever, and if they don't

00:37:14.339 --> 00:37:18.510
establish a track record, you know, we're
going to work hard to move you out.

00:37:18.510 --> 00:37:25.680
So votes are important, and communicating
your impatience with your elected representatives

00:37:25.680 --> 00:37:30.210
is important.
They do understand that they have to get reelected.

00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:35.910
And, if you cast it just that starkly, that
plays a big role.

00:37:35.910 --> 00:37:42.190
We're not going to do it individually; we're
going to do it through national and international

00:37:42.190 --> 00:37:44.030
policy and leverage.
Thank you.

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:54.819
Q Hi. I was wondering if you could -- I know
this is a complex subject -- but try and explain

00:37:54.819 --> 00:38:00.800
the cooling and warming model a little bit.
Because -- to me, who is sort of untrained

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:06.880
in this -- ice and carbon seem like two different
things.

00:38:06.880 --> 00:38:12.130
And if we factor out people, you know, you
talked about reflectivity, and that completely

00:38:12.130 --> 00:38:13.451
makes sense.
I can see that.

00:38:13.451 --> 00:38:20.010
But, if I apply that to the past Ice Age,
it would seem like, "Oh, we'd never warm up

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:22.660
again.
Because as the ice got thicker and thicker,

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:27.369
we'd get more and more reflective, and then
there'd be nothing to tip the balance back.”

00:38:27.369 --> 00:38:30.650
And so, there must be something.
And so, I was wondering if you can kind of

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:31.650
unify that model?

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:35.329
Dr. Henry Pollack: Yeah, well, it's not my
unification.

00:38:35.329 --> 00:38:40.500
It has been, of course, studied intensively.
And, in fact, ice ages do end.

00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:44.470
And they're followed by rapid warming.
But part of the end of ice ages has to do

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:49.640
with orbital factors in the Earth and its
orbit about the sun.

00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:56.990
And that, the tilt of the Earth's axis -- which
is today about 23 and a half degrees from

00:38:56.990 --> 00:39:02.990
the plane of our orbit about the sun -- that
actually oscillates between 21 and 24 degrees.

00:39:02.990 --> 00:39:11.850
And the shape of the ellipse about the sun
oscillates with a period about 100,000 years.

00:39:11.850 --> 00:39:17.880
And the procession of the equinoxes, which
determines which hemisphere is getting more

00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:24.309
sunshine in June or December -- that has a
period in the low 20,000 years.

00:39:24.309 --> 00:39:28.809
And those factors are the big pacemakers of
the ice age.

00:39:28.809 --> 00:39:35.880
But, what we've noticed is that -- throughout
the ice ages -- temperature and carbon dioxide

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:40.569
have marched together.
Now, the lesson of that is that, the two are

00:39:40.569 --> 00:39:45.049
strongly coupled.
That the temperature and the carbon cycle

00:39:45.049 --> 00:39:51.839
are tied together.
And whenever either one gets out in the lead,

00:39:51.839 --> 00:39:55.800
it pulls the other along.
So, if the temperature were to warm, it would

00:39:55.800 --> 00:40:00.910
pull the carbon dioxide up.
If the carbon dioxide is added, quite independently

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:02.980
of temperature, it would pull the temperature
up.

00:40:02.980 --> 00:40:09.950
In the current world, we are pulling carbon
dioxide way out ahead of temperature, and

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:16.050
the temperature is starting to catch up.
And so, yes, there are the long period, orbital

00:40:16.050 --> 00:40:22.400
factors that play a role, but right now, we
are pulling carbon out of the Earth, and sending

00:40:22.400 --> 00:40:27.080
it back to the atmosphere at a pace that it
hasn't seen for over a million years -- probably

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:28.080
many million years.

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:37.690
Q So I can imagine how we can adapt to rising
sea levels and missing ice.

00:40:37.690 --> 00:40:44.330
I'm more concerned about ocean acidification.
I wonder if you have any insider words to

00:40:44.330 --> 00:40:48.970
add about how dramatically the ecology of
the oceans will shift as the pH drops?

00:40:48.970 --> 00:40:57.850
Dr. Henry Pollack: Well, there's quite a well-established,
observational data about the slow decline

00:40:57.850 --> 00:41:04.049
in the pH.
And the oceans are still not acidic in the

00:41:04.049 --> 00:41:10.849
technical sense, but they're approaching -- they're
becoming less alkaline and approaching acidity.

00:41:10.849 --> 00:41:18.110
And that, of course, does affect any of the
organisms that use calcification as the way

00:41:18.110 --> 00:41:21.770
of building their shells or their reefs or
whatever.

00:41:21.770 --> 00:41:29.049
We're just beginning to see studies that show
that coral reefs are having trouble.

00:41:29.049 --> 00:41:34.530
Some of the bivalves on the ocean floor -- their
shells are thinning.

00:41:34.530 --> 00:41:39.680
And so, it's at a stage now where you're getting
all the early warning signs.

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:47.700
But, just as we need to stabilize our emissions
into the atmosphere -- after all, that is

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:55.210
what is driving the decrease in pH in the
oceans is that, the oceans are asking to absorb

00:41:55.210 --> 00:42:00.990
more and more of the carbon dioxide from the
atmosphere, and they do that, but it's changing

00:42:00.990 --> 00:42:05.140
the pH.
Where it's going to take us is not so clear

00:42:05.140 --> 00:42:08.060
to me.
I'm not a biologist, and I don't have that

00:42:08.060 --> 00:42:12.690
insight.
But, it's a very real problem, because the

00:42:12.690 --> 00:42:22.510
marine environment, of course, is a huge source
of human nourishment, and to see that be impacted

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:28.069
in this way is ominous.
Now, I might add that there are schemes afoot

00:42:28.069 --> 00:42:33.280
to block sunshine.
It's called geo-engineering or climate-engineering,

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:40.900
by putting artificial pollution into the atmosphere
to reflect sunshine away or to spray water

00:42:40.900 --> 00:42:43.640
vapor into the atmosphere to promote cloud
formation.

00:42:43.640 --> 00:42:50.880
All of that is to, kind of, mechanically interfere
with sunshine reaching the Earth, but that

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:58.109
doesn't do anything for the problem you cited.
If we're still pumping out carbon dioxide

00:42:58.109 --> 00:43:03.410
and trying to adjust climate by reducing sunshine,
the carbon dioxide is still going to go into

00:43:03.410 --> 00:43:10.681
the ocean and lead to a drop in pH.
So I think that the geo-engineering or climate-engineering

00:43:10.681 --> 00:43:19.940
solutions are shortsighted if they focus only
on blocking sunshine.

00:43:19.940 --> 00:43:24.520
Q Apologies if you covered this earlier in
your talk, but methane is one of the other

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:30.360
large contributors to effects in the atmosphere.
And we have, you know, billion of tons of

00:43:30.360 --> 00:43:35.150
biomass in the Arctic that's thawing out and
