It seems to me that could have a pretty disastrous
impact on the behavior of the atmosphere and

00:43:40.770 --> 00:43:42.410
I was wondering.

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:48.950
Dr. Henry Pollack: The comment that, as the
regions around the Arctic are thawing out,

00:43:48.950 --> 00:43:53.470
the permafrost degrading.
And that, there's a lot of methane locked

00:43:53.470 --> 00:43:58.270
in the permafrost that's making its way to
the atmosphere.

00:43:58.270 --> 00:44:03.010
And that's all true.
And there is also methane stored in ice just

00:44:03.010 --> 00:44:08.420
below the ocean floor, which has a huge amount
of methane that, if it were destabilized and

00:44:08.420 --> 00:44:14.559
went into the atmosphere that, it too, would
add to the greenhouse gas burden of the atmosphere.

00:44:14.559 --> 00:44:20.319
About the melting of the permafrost -- once
again, kind of the first stage of measurements

00:44:20.319 --> 00:44:26.130
in the permafrost lakes that are developing
 -- show -- yes, indeed -- there is a methane

00:44:26.130 --> 00:44:33.020
flux.
And how fast that will penetrate -- the melting

00:44:33.020 --> 00:44:37.849
will penetrate -- and release more, is the
big question.

00:44:37.849 --> 00:44:45.130
Most calculations of the diffusion of heat
downward to melt the permafrost and release

00:44:45.130 --> 00:44:54.880
the methane, shows that it's not a fast problem.
It's one that would progress slowly and have

00:44:54.880 --> 00:45:02.220
a time scale that would be in the centuries,
rather than an immediate belching out of large

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:11.500
amounts of methane.
So while it's nothing to trivialize, it's

00:45:11.500 --> 00:45:18.350
not something that's going to overwhelm us
with a very fast and furious feedback into

00:45:18.350 --> 00:45:19.350
the greenhouse.

